{{primarysources|date=August 2011}} {{Infobox software | name = Tomboy | logo = [[File:Tomboy logo.svg]] | screenshot = [[File:Tomboy 0.10.2 main screen.png|300px]] | caption = Tomboy linking between notes | collapsible = | developer = Alex Graveley | status = Active | latest_release_version = 1.6.0 | latest_release_date = {{Start date and age|2011|04|05}} | latest_preview_version = 1.7.6 | latest_preview_date = {{Start date and age|2011|09|05}} | operating_system = [[Cross-platform]] | programming_language = [[C Sharp (programming language)|C#]] | platform = [[Mono (software)|Mono]], [[GTK+]] | genre = [[Notetaking]] application | license = [[GNU Lesser General Public License|GNU LGPL]] | website = {{URL|projects.gnome.org/tomboy}} }}
[[File:Tomboy 0.10.2 example note.png|thumb|Example note.]] '''Tomboy''' is a [[free and open source software|free and open-source]] desktop [[notetaking]] application written for [[Unix-like]] (including [[Mac OS X]]) and [[Microsoft Windows]] operating systems,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://projects.gnome.org/tomboy/ | title = Tomboy: Simple note taking | date = June 25, 2009 | accessdate = July 5, 2009 }}</ref> written in [[C Sharp (programming language)|C#]] using [[Gtk Sharp|Gtk#]]. Tomboy is part of the [[GNOME]] desktop environment, often for [[personal information management]]. Its interface is a notepad with a [[wiki#Linking and creating pages|wiki]]-like linking system to connect notes together. Words in the note body that match extant note titles become hyperlinks automatically, making it simple to construct a [[personal wiki]]. For example, repeated references to favorite artists would automatically be highlighted in notes containing their names.
==Features== Some of the editing features supported: * Text highlighting * Inline spell checking using GtkSpell * Auto-linking of web and email addresses * Undo/redo * Font styling and sizing * Bulleted lists * Note synchronization over [[Secure Shell|SSH]], [[WebDAV]], [[Ubuntu One]], or Snowy<ref>{{cite web | url = http://live.gnome.org/Snowy | title = Snowy - GNOME Live! | date = 2010-09-14 | accessdate = 2010-10-04 }}</ref> ([[Affero General Public License|AGPL]] Django web app for online access to Tomboy notes)
==Plugins== Tomboy supports several plugins, including: * [[Evolution (software)|Evolution]] mail links * [[Galago (software)|Galago]]/[[Pidgin (software)|Pidgin]] presence * Note of the day (disabled by default) * Fixed width text * [[HTML]] export * [[LaTeX]] math (in the package <tt>tomboy-latex</tt>, not installed by default) * Print
==Ports== * Conboy is a Tomboy port to the [[Maemo]] platform written in the [[C (programming language)|C]] language<ref>[https://garage.maemo.org/projects/conboy Conboy]</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://garage.maemo.org/projects/conboy | title = garage: Conboy - Note Taking Application: Project Info | date = September 16, 2009 | accessdate = September 16, 2009 }}</ref> * [[Gnote]] is a conversion of the Tomboy code to the [[C++]] language * Tomdroid is an effort to produce a tomboy client for the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] mobile platform.<ref>[https://launchpad.net/tomdroid Tomdroid]</ref> "The goal is to be file format compatible and be able to sync notes with tomboy"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://automorphic.blogspot.com/2009/04/tomboy-notes-on-android-olivier.html | title = Tomboy Notes on Android: Olivier Bilodeau Releases Tomdroid 0.1.0 | date=April 21, 2009 | accessdate = January 3, 2010 }}</ref>
